@inproceedings{wright1991neuromotor,
  title = {Neuromotor maturation and the ontogeny of ultrasonic vocalizations in the California mouse (peromyscus californicus) Ten female and eleven male P. californicuspups from 8 litters were individually marked, weighed and tested for ultrasonic vocalizations (UVs). UVs, locomotion, surface righting, negative geotaxis, acoustic startle reflex and eye opening were recorded from 2 to 30 days of age. UVs at 37, 42, 47 and 52 kHz were digitized and recorded by computer and an event recorder program which was simultaneously used to record locomotor behaviour. Results were analyzed by sex of pup and litter size. Put weight was • negatively correlated with UVs (r=-.58, p<.05). UVs decreased as pups aged (p<.01). Females vocalized more than males (p<.01) and vocalizationsincreased for both males and females after they spent more than 180 sin coordinated movement (p<0.01). There was no effect of litter siu on UVs. After the auditory startle reflex was shown, UVs decreased significantly (p<.01). Although there was no effect of eye openingon UVs, pups from litters of two opened their eyes earlier than pups from larger litters p<.01). Males opened their eyes earlier than females (p<.05). These results indicate that P. californicus has a pattern of UV development that is related to weight, age, sex, development of coordinated movement and auditory startle reflex. Surface righting, negative geotaxis and eye opening were not related to the developmentof UVs.},
