  title = {Identification, starting at the top Viewing the same object from different angles results in different retinal images. We are able to recognize these different visual inputs as the same object This is known as object constancy. When line drawings of familiar objects are presented to subjects, the time to name the object increases linearly for objects rotated up to 120 degrees from the vertical. This function suggests that during object identification, the input is being normalized to the upright, until a match is found in memory. Biederman (1989) has suggested that the effects of orientation are due to finding the top of the object In order to test this hypothesis, valid and invalid precues of object orientation will be presented prior to the display of the object to be named. If the effect of orientation is in finding the top, as Biederman has suggested then the valid cue condition should show less of an effect of orientation than the invalid cue.},
