@inproceedings{schellinck1991discriminati,
  title = {Discrimination of human male odours by rats is not influenced by the relatedness of the urine donors Rats can be trained in an olfactometer to discriminate between the urine odours of MHC congenic rats and mice. They learn these discriminations quickly and remember the information from one daily session to another. Such results indicate that constant odour cues are used to discriminate between these urines (Schellinck, Brown and Slotnick, Anim,Learn,Behay,. in press). To determine if rats can discriminate between human urines, we tested five Long-Evans rats in a go/no discrimination in an olfactometer. Discriminable differences were present in urines from monozyotic twins, dizogotic twins, siblings and unrelated males. Analysis of the erros to criterion over eight 200 trial sessions indicated that the four human urine odour discriminations were equally difficult to learn. Although all test rats were able to discriminate the urine pairs to a criterion of 90% correct within one or more of the eight sessions, only one of the rats was able to maintain this level of performance from session to session. The other four subjects either relearned the discrimination within a session or performed at chance levels on subsequent sessions. When the ability of rats to learn to discriminate between the urine odours of rats, mice and humans is compared, it appears that constant cues are being used to discriminate between the urine odours of rats and mice whereas this is not the case for hwnan urine odours.},
