  year = {1997},
  abstract = {This paper addresses the translation of Borderline and Histrionic personality disorders into the language of the Five-Factor model of personality. Based on theoretical expectations, we investigated the empirical relationship between the Five-Factors of personality and these two personality disorders in a non-clinical sample. As expected, the personality disorders were characterized by high levels of Neuroticism. For Borderline personality disorder, our expectations regarding Agreeableness were confirmed, however, those for Extraversion were not As well, additional relationships were found between both Openness and Conscientiousness and Borderline personality disorder. For Histrionic personality disorder, our expectations for Extraversion were confirmed, however, those for Openness were not Additionally, both Agreeableness and Conscientiousness demonstrated and unexpected relationship with Histrionic personality disorder. While some of the expected relationships between the Five-Factors and Borderline and Histrionic personality were confirmed. others were not It appears that theoretical or clinical expectations are not necessarily confirmed by empirical findings in a non-clinical sample. Results are discussed in terms of the utility of the Five-Factor model in describing personality disorders.},
