ased on the application of a magnetic field and its modulation with a radio-frequency pulse. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) offers insight into regional morphology. Magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS) offers a non-invasive brain biopsy of neurochemistry. Functional MRI (fMRI) offers a window into brain function via regional brain activation and oxyhemoglobin and deoxyhemoglobin exchange. Diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) tracts white matter coherence and will be especially use},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T16-split1-split1 at: 'T19. An investigation of the phonologica'},
}

@inproceedings{darcy2000transcallosa,
  title = {Transcallosal While Matter Activation Revealed by Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging During Reading},
  author = {D'Arcy, Ryan C.N and Connolly, John F and MacMaster, Frank P and Vandorpe, Robert and Gates, Larry and Darvesh, Sultan},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Functional :MRI has been used to demonstrate gray matter activation associated with sensory and cognitive functions. We provide the first evidence of f:MRI activation in white matter. This activation was observed in comrrtissural fiber tracts passing through the splenium of the corpus callosum during sentence reading. The time course data from white matter voxels revealed that, like gray matter activation, the responses were time-locked to the stimulus presentation. However, as expected, the white matter peak amplitudes were markedly attenuated relative to the responses in the visual cortex. Reliability of the white matter activation was established by replicating fully the effect in a participant following a six-month interval. The active white matter regions localized the comrrtissural fibers that connect functionally specialized visual word form areas. These findings provide the first noninvasive identification of the neural architecture involved in sentence reading.},
}

@inproceedings{wang2000investigatioa,
  title = {An investigation of the phonological processing in Chinese language with ERPs},
  author = {Wang, Jingtian and Connolly, John},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Two unique features of Chinese language draw much attention and interest in psycholinguistics. The first is that Chinese written language is pictographic. There is an opaque relationship between the pronunciation and physical appearance of a Chinese character. For example, homophones have the exact same pronunciation but completely different script feature and meaning. This opacity of the script-to- sound relationship has led to a widespread assumption that readers of Chinese can arrive at the mental lexicon by identifying a whole character visually, without any involvement with phonological coding. The issue of whether there is phonological code involved in Chinese reading was investigated with the recording of ERPs. The other specific feature of Chinese language is that it is a tone language. Most Chinese characters consist of monosyllables with an affiliated lexical tone and the tonality of a monosyllable is lexically meaningful. Though the perception of tone plays a major role in Chinese speech comprehension, little is known about its underlying electrophysiological basis. What's more, in behavioral studies, there is a major issue of whether tone perception is of importance in Chinese reading comprehension since there are more errors in tone discrimination tasks during Chinese reading. My future experiments will mainly focus on the above issues with the recording of ERPs, the measurement of brain electrical activity that is time-locked to the underlying linguistic processing.},
}

@inproceedings{clark2000form,
  title = {Form or Function? A body-image assessment tool},
  author = {Clark, Sharon and Gusella, Joanne and Roosmalen, Erica van},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {A negative body image is one of the primary features of an eating disorder and often develops from an exclusive focus on body appearance, or the form of one's body, rather than considering the functional aspects of how the body works. We developed and conducted testing of a new assessment measure of body image. This measure compares two dimensions of body image perceptions: form and function. It was hypothesized that if the functional activities of the body are emphasized, and contrasted to what is liked about the body, the discrepancy between form and function would become apparent. This may be an important component in changing cognitive distortions involved in body image problems while beginning to create a sense of appreciation for what one's body does rather than what it looks like. Results of pilot testing with the measure will be presented.},
}

@inproceedings{macmaster2000magnetic,
  title = {Magnetic Resonance in Psychiatry},
  author = {MacMaster, Frank P and Khan, Shakeela and Kusumakar, Vivek},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {In reference to the invention of the stethoscope, P.A. Piorry remarked "If this method had only a quarter of the utility attributed to it. . .it would still be one of the most precious discoveries of medicine". The same can be said of magnetic resonance (MR). MR technology offers exciting insight into neurobiology, and the main modalities and their application will be reviewed here. MR is based on the application of a magnetic field and its modulation with a radio-frequency pulse. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) offers insight into regional morphology. Magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS) offers a non-invasive brain biopsy of neurochemistry. Functional MRI (fMRI) offers a window into brain function via regional brain activation and oxyhemoglobin and deoxyhemoglobin exchange. Diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) tracts white matter coherence and will be especially useful in studies of development. MR, as it uses non-ionizing radiation, is an especially valuable tool for the investigation of pediatric populations. Potential applications in neural development, neuropathology and drug trials will be discussed.},
}

@inproceedings{kahn2000neurobiologi,
  title = {Neurobiological Discriminations of ADHD and Bipolar Disorder},
  author = {Kahn, Shakeela and MacMaster, Frank and Connolly, John and Carrey, Normand and Eskes, Gail and Gates, Larry and Kutcher, Stan and Kusumakar, Vivek},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Both Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder and Bipolar Disorder are characterized by behavioral and cognitive deficits that can negatively impact on crucial aspects of life such as academic, social and family functioning, as well as enormous financial burden on society. The goal of treatment is to intervene as early as possible and interrupt the course of the illness. Unfortunately, childhood onset of Bipolar disorder often presents with symptoms similar to ADHD (attention deficit hyperactivity disorder). This can result in misinterpretation of attention deficit and impulsivity and misdiagnosis of both conditions in childhood. The consequences of misdiagnosis can be severe. Thus, early, accurate detection of ADHD and bipolar disorder is vital to the management of the illnesses in the long term. The current management of this problem involves waiting and monitoring the course of the illness; an undesirable option given the evidence for neuronal deterioration and severity that accompanies the natural progression of bipolar disorder (Drevets et al., 1997). One focus of the Dept of Psychiatry at the IWK Grace is to develop neurobiological diagnostic tools to distinguish between ADHD and bipolar disorder at an early age, with the goal of intervening as early as possible. These research directions as well as past research in the area will be discussed.},
}

@inproceedings{braaksma2000evaluation,
  title = {An evaluation of the Bispectral Index (BIS) as a valid monitor of depth of anaesthesia},
  author = {Braaksma, Deanna and Finley, Allen and Connolly, John and Houlihan, Michael and McGrath, Patrick},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The BIS index monitor (BIS) (Aspect Medical Systems Inc.) is a relatively new technique that Anaesthesiologists might use to measure anesthetic depth. Aspect claims that BIS is the first clinically proven, direct measure of the effects of anesthesia on the conscious state of patients. However, BIS was not developed to assess cognitive processes. It was merely designed in reference to an observer's assessment of depth of anesthesia (e.g., autonomic responses, movement, blood concentrations). Is the BIS monitor a valid clinical tool for assessing consciousness during anaesthesia? Two approaches are proposed to provide anesthesiologists with stronger, better evidence to base their clinical decisions regarding the BIS monitor: (1) asystematic review/ meta-analysis to comprehensively synthesize the literature on BIS index values and various outcome measures of anesthetic depth, and (2) experimental studies examining sensory and language processing using event-related potentials during anesthesia in adult volunteers at various BIS index values.},
}

@inproceedings{houlihan2000bump,
  title = {1 bump, 2 bump, old bump, new bump: Using event-related potential maps to identify functionally independent components in ERPs.},
  author = {Houlihan, Michael},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Event-related potentials (ERPs) are the electrical signal recorded from a scalp that has been time-locked to a particular event and averaged across many repetitions of the event. ERPs provide a signature of the cortical processing of an event or stimulus with excellent temporal resolution. Advances in computing power and electronics in general have made it possible to record ERPs at many locations over the scalp, introducing an improvement in spatial localization of cognitive processes. ERPs are analyzed by examining the amplitude, spatial distribution and timing of the amplitude. ERP components are usually identified visually as peaks and valleys at each location. If ERP components overlap temporally and spatially they are difficult to impossible to separate. Several solutions to the separation of components have been tested over the years with none adequately filling the role. Recently, an approach to "blind separation" called independent component analysis (ICA), has been applied to neurophysiological signals. ICA has been used with ERPs and fMRI for identifying independent patterns in the data, as onset and duration measures and for the elimination of artifact (muscle activity; EOG; cardiac signals). Examples of the use of ICA will be presented and discussed.},
}

@inproceedings{marchand2000model,
  title = {Model of reading aloud: computational and fMRI investigations.},
  author = {Marchand, Yan nick},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The ability to transform orthographic (letter string) information into phonological (speech sound) information underlies our ability to read words aloud, and it is one of the most important skills we learn. It is often argued that various facts about reading is explained by a model which assumes the existence of a dual-route architecture (lexical and nonlexical routes from print to speech). In this talk, we present some possible cross-fertilizations between a single-route computational model of reading aloud and functional neuroimaging.},
}

@inproceedings{mayo2000strategy,
  title = {Strategy versus ability in speech perception: Behavioural and ERP studies.},
  author = {Mayo, Catherine},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Early speech perception research centred on the impressive abilities of the human perceptual system. In particular, such research made much of listeners' tendency to perceive gradually varying speech stimuli in terms of a limited number of meaningful phonological categories. Current ERP research has focussed on determining neural correlates of this ability. However, more recent perceptual research has shown that while normal listeners show very similar perceptual abilities, the strategies which individual listeners employ to reach a percept will often differ. This talk will discuss current behavioural studies, which have shown developmental differences in perceptual strategies. The talk will conclude with a discussion of the potential for ERP studies to further our understanding of perceptual strategy differences.},
}

@inproceedings{penner2000does,
  title = {Does Vagus Nerve Stimulation for the Treatment of Medically Refractory Seizures Enhance Memory?},
  author = {Penner, Marsha and Valdivia, Ivan},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Pharmacology and Departments of Psychology Dalhousie University & QEII HSC Epilepsy can have a profound impact on all aspects of a person's life. A novel treatment, vagus nerve stimulation (VNS), has recently been introduced to treat medically refractory seizures. Despite some promising effects on seizure frequency, little information is available regarding the effect of VNS on cognitive functioning. A recent report in Nature Neuroscience indicates that VNS enhances recognition memory in human subjects (Clark et al, 1999). However, this report has not been substantiated by other groups. The present study examines memory function in a group of patients being treated with the vagal nerve stimulator for medically refractory seizures. Subjective and objective memory measures, including the Memory Observation Questionnaire and the Weschsler Memory Sc.ale-UTan~ administered immediately before implantation of the stimulator and againat a follow-up visit one year later. Outcome measures from the VNS patient group are compared to two control groups, including a group of patients who have undergone temporal resectioning, and a group of patients maintained on antiepileptic medication.},
}

@inproceedings{marchant2000getting,
  title = {Getting Hip on the Chip •• /- ' ··: > -· ) .,?71--.-h/:__:,;__,1},
  author = {Marchant, Elliott and Goguen, Donna and deGroot, Marleen and Rusak, Ben},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {This talk will outline new technology that provides efficient access to genetic information using miniaturized high-density arrays of oligonucleotide probes. This technology is currently is being used by the Rusak lab in collaboration with Novartis Institute for Functional Genomics and Affymetrix, to explore the molecular impact of light on the mouse suprachiasmatic nucleus. ,, (~ .r 1 • ~- " I• 1 ~ •·1~1 ~ '•../•I'., _)_./},
}

@inproceedings{groot2000meals,
  title = {Meals on Wheels},
  author = {Groot, Marleen de and Marchant, Elliott and Rusak, Ben},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Animals exposed to schedules of temporally restricted food access will begin to anticipate the arrival of food after a number of days on the schedule, typically by increasing activity, such as wheel-running. This anticipatory activity is regulated by a self-sustaining, endogenous pacemaker that is both structurally and functionally distinct from the master circadian pacemaker. The identity of this food- entrainable pacemaker and the nature of the afferent signals that affect it remain unknown. We are investigating which brain regions may be involved in the acquisition and expression of food anticipatory activity. We have recently assessed patterns of immediate-early gene (IEG) expression in various brain regions in mice who have been acutely food deprived or exposed to a repeated daily schedule of food access. The preliminary data showing the effects of refeeding on IEG expression in these two groups of mice will be discussed. . . ,c, / J ·},
}

@inproceedings{barresi2000intentional,
  title = {Intentional relations and divergent perspectives in social understanding},
  author = {Barresi, John},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {People are very skilled at applying folk-psychological concepts uniformly to self and other. Thus, I understand your being in love in much the same way that I understand my being in love. But the information I have about you being in love is hardly the same as the information that I have about me being in love. This informational difference can sometimes lead to divergent interpretations of human actions between actors and observers. Not surprisingly, social psychologists, always on the lookout for differences rather than commonalities, have stressed this divergence rather than the commonality in social understanding, naming it the 'actor-observer effect'. In the present paper, I extend a model of social understanding developed by Barresi & Moore (1996) to account for divergent interpretations of actions, not only between actors and observers, but also between members of different social groups.},
}

@inproceedings{lee2000effects,
  title = {Effects of lesions of the medial preoptic area on parental behaviour in male and female California mice, Peromyscus californicus},
  author = {Lee, Anna W. and Brown, Richard E.},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Peromyscus californicus are monogamous and bi parental mice. The male shows all aspects of parental care, except lactation, as soon as the pups are born. Thus, they are an ideal species in which to compare the neuroanatomical basis of maternal and paternal behaviour. The present study investigated the effects of lesions in the medial preoptic area on the expression of parental behaviour in male and female California mice. Electrolytic or sham lesions were performed two days postpartum on a male or female from each male-female pair. Mice were tested for parental responsiveness for 10 days, beginning one day post surgery. Preliminary results suggest that medial preoptic lesions disrupt parental behaviour in both male and female mice.},
}

@inproceedings{christensen2000lateral,
  title = {Lateral Hypothalamic Lesions Disrupt Time-Place Learning in Rats},
  author = {Christensen, C. and Gregus, A. and Luedeman, K. and MacKinnon, S. and Oliver, B. and Pitman, J. and Taggart, J. and Groot, Marleen de and Marchant, Elliott},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Time-place learning refers to situations in which an animal learns to associate a particular time of day with a particular location. The acquisition of the association between temporal and spatial information has previously been studied in various species. In order to investigate whether the lateral hypothalamus (LH) plays a role in time-place learning, intact (n=6) and LB-lesioned (n=4) rats were trained to obtain food at two distinct locations, each at a different time of day. A standard two lever T-maze was used in this study. Rats were rewarded for lever presses on the left side during morning session and on the right side during afternoon sessions. All 10 rats learned the task, however, omission tests showed that LH lesioned animals performed worse than intact animals, suggesting that lesioned animals were using a different strategy. The results indicate that the LH may be an important structure involved in time-place learning.},
}

@inproceedings{klages2000there,
  title = {Is there a relation between Apolipoprotein E gene status and neuropsychological memory test performance? An analysis of the Canadian Study of Health and Aging},
  author = {Klages, Jennifer and Fisk, John D.},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The current identified risk factors for Alzheimer's disease (AD) have insufficient predictive value. One is the presence of ;E4allele of the Apolipoprotein (APOE) gene. Poor performance on neuropsychologicaitestsis another. We examined the relation between these two risk factors in a population-based sample of people over age 64. Participants were enrolled in the Canadian Study of Health and Aging (CSHA), a nationwide study of the prevalence of dementia that involved over 10,000 people. APOE status was determined in1578 of which 1188 had no E4 allele and 390 had at least one ~le. From this group, 1123 had n~ __cog~iti~ impai~ (Ng, 268 had cognitive impairment but not dementia (CIND) and 187 had dementia. Neuropsycholog1cal test performance of subjects with and without the E4 allele was c-ompared within these di~c categories. NCI subjects who had an E4 allele performed worse on two memory tests: th~ued RecaliTest(p<.004) and the Rey Auditory Verbal Leaming Test (p<0.05). APOE status was not related to test performance for the CIND or demented groups and was not related toperformance on any other tests. APOE status -and memory test performance have some relationship in nondemented elderly. Together, these factors may help to predict the development of dementia at followup.},
}

@inproceedings{gamblers2000alcohol,
  title = {Alcohol effects on Risk-Taking during Video Lottery Terminal (VLT) Play Among Pathological},
  author = {Gamblers, and Non-Pathological},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Mike Ellery, Sherry H. Stewart, Pamela Loba, James R. Blackburn, & Raymond Klein As part of an ongoing study, four risk-taking variables were examined in order to test the hypothesis that alcohol consumption would lead to increased risk taking during gambling play, particularly for pathological gamblers. Participants were regular video lottery terminal (VLT) players, recruited by newspaper advertisement in the community. An equal number of the participants run thus far were assigned to alcohol and no alcohol control conditions (N = 10 per beverage condition). Eight of the 20 (N =4 per beverage condition) met criteria for probable pathological gambling, as assessed by the South Oaks Gambling Screen (SOOS; Lesieur & Blume, 1987), and the remaining 12 scored below the SOOS cutoff, indicating non-pathological gambling status (N =6 per beverage condition). Participants were randomly assigned to either the moderately intoxicating dose of alcohol condition, or the control beverage condition (mix only). Following beverage consumption and absorption, participants were allowed to play a poker game on a commercially available VLT for up to 30 minutes. Four indices of risk-taking were recorded throughout gambling play: (a) number of times participants hit the "powerbet" button (which allows gamblers to double their bet size after having viewed only two cards of their five card poker hand); (b) total money inserted into machine during entire 30 minutes of play (in Canadian dollars); (c) average bet size during the last 5 minutes of play (also in Canadian dollars); and (d) total time out of a possible 30 minute play period that subjects chose to play machines (measured in minutes). Results of preliminary planned comparison analyses provide evidence that: (1) alcohol consumption increases risk taking behaviour while gambling, but only among pathological (and not non-pathological) gamblers, and (2) increased risk taking is displayed by pathological relative to non-pathological gamblers during VLT play, but only when they are intoxicated, and not when they are sober. Theoretical and clinical implications of the findings will be discussed.},
}

@inproceedings{shoemaker2000trade,
  title = {Trade-offs between current and future reproduction in the cricket, Gryllus integer},
  author = {Shoemaker, Kelly and Adamo, Shelley},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {In order to maximize lifetime reproductive success, organisms must often make trade-offs between current and future reproductive effort. We examined these trade-offs in the cricket, Gryllus integer, in response to predation risk and infection: two factors that could potentially reduce future reproductive output to zero. We found that G. integer females laid more eggs when the egg-laying substrate was covered than when exposed. However, G. integer females did not lay more eggs following infection with a potentially lethal pathogen, Serratia marcescens. These results suggest the G. integer females regulate oviposition based on predation risk, but that it is not influenced by immune status.},
}

@inproceedings{patterson2000accumulation,
  title = {Accumulation, Reactivity, and Adaptation Models of Event and Mood Relationships},
  author = {Patterson, Robin L. and Santor, Darcy A.},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Many studies examining the relation between events and mood employ a 2-wave panel design in which events and mood are assessed at two time points. This assumes that the effects of events accumulate and persist until mood is assessed at follow-up. This design is inadequate to assess mood reactivity or individual adaptation. The present study examined three models of event and mood relationships: accumulation, reactivity, and adaptability. Participants (N=102) completed mood and event checklists twice weekly for 10 weeks. These checklists involved recording events and tracking moods and behaviors. The results showed little evidence for the accumulation model. Results supported models that tested reactivity and adaptation. Both positive and negative events influenced negative moods; however, few negative events resulted in lasting mood disturbances. Mood disturbances that were precipitated by a negative event lasted less than six days. Results have implications for how events are assessed and the types of proposed models.},
}

@inproceedings{mcfadyen2000effects,
  title = {Effects of Chronic Methylphenidate Administration at Several Stages of Development in CD-1 Mice},
  author = {McFadyen, Melanie and Penner, Marsha and Lewis, Stephen and Carrey, Normand and Brown, Richard},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Although methylphenidate hydrochloride (MPH, Ritalin) has been used in the treatment of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) for several decades, research examining the potential effects of MPH on neurobehavioural development is lacking. We have conducted several experiments that begin to systematically detail the effects of different doses of MPH administered at different times during development (prenatal, neonatal/infancy, and prepubertal). Mice exposed to MPH (5 mg/kg) prenatally (embryonic days (E) 8-10 or El2-14) exhibited significant increases in spontaneous locomotion when tested at postnatal days (PND) 3-11. No differences were observed in tests of neuromotor reflexes such as righting, negative geotaxis, or forelimb grip strength. In adulthood, the mice exposed to MPH from E8-10 exhibited significantly increased exploration in both the open field and the elevated plus maze, as well as decreased anxiety in the elevated plus maze. Chronic MPH administration (5 or 20 mg/kg) during postnatal development (PND3- l 1) resulted in significant increases in locomotion, but had no effect on ultrasonic vocalizations when pups were tested one hour after each injection. In adulthood, these mice performed equally well in the Morris water maze, showing no deficits in either learning or memory in this cognitive spatial task. No doses of MPH (2.5, 5, 10, 20, 40, or 80 mg/kg) administered during prepubertal development (PND26-32) had an effect on spontaneous locomotion, exploration, fear or anxiety in the open field and elevated plus maze when the mice were tested at PND 33. There was no effect of any dose of MPH on learning and memory in the Morris water maze when mice were tested from 34-37 days of age. The results of our experiments suggest that while acute administration of MPH does elevate locomotor activity, chronic administration has no enduring deleterious effects on neuromotor reflexes, learning or memory. Experiments examining longer administration times, MPH exposure at different stages of development, and effects of MPH in animal models of ADHD are necessary in order to fully establish the safety of MPH exposure during development.},
}

@inproceedings{stanford2000effects,
  title = {Effects of the Benzodiazepine Receptor Agonist Chlordiazepoxide & the 5-HTlA Antagonist WAY100635 on Behaviour in the Rat Elevated Zero Maze are not Influenced by the Light/Dark Cycle.},
  author = {Stanford, Lianne},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The rat elevated zero maze is a validated model of anxiety (Shepherd et al. 1994 Psychopharm 116:56- 64). In this test, rats administered anxiolytic drugs typically show a behavioural profile of increased exploratory activity (line crosses & head dips), increased time in the open areas, and less risk assessment (stretch-attends). In mice, 5-HTlA receptor antagonists have altered profiles on the elevated plus-maze when tested during different portions of the light/dark cycle (Rodgers et al., 1998 J Psychopharm 12:A32). To investigate this further, rats housed under normal or reversed light/dark cycles were tested with chlordiazepoxide (CDP), a benzodiazepine receptor agonist or with WA Yl00635, a 5-HTlA receptor antagonist. CDP (4 mg/kg) treated rats showed a similar anxiolytic profile in both housing groups. WA Yl00635 (0.01 to 0.3 mg/kg, sc: 30min) was without effect on rats from either housing group. These data show that the time of testing relative to the diurnal cycle does not alter the profiles of either CDP or WA Y100635, and question the assumption that time of testing is a critical determinant of the anxiolytic properties of 5-HTlA receptor antagonists.},
}

@inproceedings{schellinck2000identificati,
  title = {The identification of pheromonal components in male mouse urine which initiate puberty acceleration in fem ale mice},
  author = {Schellinck, l . J-r-/ Heather and Clarke, Allison and Brown, Richard and Wilkinson, Michael},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The pheromonal components of male mouse urine which accelerate puberty in female mice have not been clearly identified. To clarify this issue, we examined the effect of a number of compounds on puberty acceleration and neural activation of the accessory olfactory bulb (AOB). During postnatal days 21-28, juvenile female mice, were exposed to male urine, major urinary proteins (MUPs), MUPs+ligands attached (2-sec-butyl-dihydrothiazole:SBT and 2,3-dehydro-exo-brevicomin:DHB ), SBT/DHB alone or saline. Puberty acceleration occurred in mice exposed to male urine or MUPS+ligands but not in mice exposed to SBT/DHB alone or MUPs alone or saline. Immediate early gene expression (c-fos) was significantly higher in the AOB of mice exposed to male urine or MUPS+ligands than in those mice exposed to saline, SBT/DHB or MUPS alone. These results indicate that exposure to specific components of male mouse urine not only induces puberty acceleration but also activates the neural pathway which initiates such a effect.},
}

@inproceedings{brown2000evolutionary,
  title = {Evolutionary origins of morality: Is there an ancestral 'logic' to the modern mind?},
  author = {Brown, William Michael},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Selfish gene theory has difficulty explaining the existence of moral impulses. Evidence from evolutionary economics suggests that individuals can forgo the temptation to cheat due to the emotions of guilt and sympathy. However genes predisposing the development of these prosocial emotions would be at a fitness disadvantage in a population of exploiters. How did sympathy evolve if it is costly to the altruist? One possible pathway is the formation of cooperator-cooperator alliances. If group formations were based upon intrinsically unfalsifiable sympathy signals, non-kin altruism may be evolutionarily stable. Perhaps the benefits to the genes involved were accrued at the within- and between-group levels of selection. Preliminary evidence that humans detect an individual's likelihood to cooperate will be presented.},
}

@inproceedings{hoffman2000remote,
  title = {Remote computing: Internet access from Far Away Places},
  author = {Hoffman, Ron and Brown, Richard},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Reliable access to the internet has become a requirement for today's academics and we take it for granted in our daily work at the university. However, when you take your work (and office) on the road (or the high seas), you need to make special arrangements to maintain that internet access. Technological advances of the recent years hold much promise for remote workers. Wireless communication is particularly enticing. In an entertaining illustrated presentation, we will discuss what worked reliably, what did not, based on our recent travels.},
}

@inproceedings{fairless2000odour,
  title = {Odour-induced egr-1 expression in the rat olfactory bulb},
  author = {Fairless, Daemon Scott},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The expression of immediate early genes (IEGs) have allowed for the mapping of neuronal activation. Both c-fos and egr-1 have been widely used to this end. While expression of c-fos seems to be induced as a function of neural activation, there is some evidence that egr-1 expression is induced only by novel stimuli. Songbirds in captivity show an increase in egr-1 expression when presented with a novel conspecific song. Induction of egr-1 decreases with repeated presentations of the same song but can be re-elicited with the presentation of a novel conspecific song. In this pilot study the effects of a novel odour on the expression of egr-1 in the rat olfactory bulb are analyzed. Animals were exposed to a novel odour (1 % propionic acid) for an hour and a half and then sacrificed. Controls were sacrificed without any novel odour stimulation. Immunoreactiviy against egr-1 in the main olfactory bulbs of each group is compared.},
}

@inproceedings{hoffman2000powerpoint,
  title = {We do PowerPoint, we do web pages, now what? Digital Video!},
  author = {Hoffman, Ron and Hannon, Vivien and MacDonald, John and Patriquin, David},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Recent technological advances in what has become known as Information Technology have changed the way we work. Chalk and blackboards are rapidly being supplanted by PowerPoint presentations, and we expect students to use that technology, too. A primary source for information is now the web (although too many students seem to see it as the only source), and our graduates need to know how to create their own web sites when they hit the job market. Now, new technologies are bringing digital video to the desktop, and we are just beginning to see the impact. We discuss these technologies, show some examples of what can be done, and ask if we should add another skill to our IT skill set.},
}

@inproceedings{klein2000mental,
  title = {Mental Geography Meets Mental Chronometry in an Exploration of the Law of "Prior Entry"},
  author = {Klein, Ray and Shore, David and Gati, J. and Menon, R.},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Abstract: It has been suggested that psychology was borne from the union of interests in mind (philosophy) and brain (physiology). Here we seek to unite two methodologies with strong connections to mind (mental chronometry) and brain (neuroimaging) in the expectation that together they will be able to do more than either could alone. Our study concerns Titchener's Fourth Law of Attention: "The stimulus, for which we are predisposed, requires less time than a like stimulus, for which we are unprepared, to produce its full conscious effect" (1908, p251). We will illustrate how this law of "prior entry" can be explored and precisely measured psychophysically by obtaining temporal order judgements for pairs of stimuli, one of which is attended. We will then present preliminary fMRI data suggesting that specific brain regions are involved in performing these judgements. Finally we will propose how event-related fMRI can be used to test Titchener's "Law of Prior Entry" and how such neuroimaging studies of prior entry can be useful in demonstrating the potential of latency-resolved fMRI.},
}

@inproceedings{shore2000there,
  title = {There is More to Tactile Perception than Simply Touch},
  author = {Shore, David I. and Spry, Emily and Spence, Charles},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {We explored the role of body position in the perception of simple tactile stimuli. The observer was presented with brief tactile vibrations to the left and right forefinger and was required to indicate which finger received the stimulus first.},
}

@inproceedings{maclnnes2000rising,
  title = {The Rising Cost of OOTLUF},
  author = {Maclnnes, Joe and McCabe, John},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Recent studies have looked at the trade-off involved in auto-pilot systems. Although automation does reduce the workload of the pilot in important tasks, it also seems to reduce the situational awareness, and produce Out of the loop unfamiliarity, (OOTLUF). This present study tested this trade-off by asking participants to navigate a set of virtual Hebb/Williams mazes, under both manual and automated conditions. Automation was simulated on alternate mazes by having participants learn a route through which they were passively transported using a previous participant's active exploration. The cost of situational awareness was measured as the increase in time to complete a maze based on the method of learning, while workload was measured through simple reaction time to random and frequent probes in both the manual and automatic conditions. Although the OOTLUF, cost of automation was observed in this experiment, the benefits to workload were not as clear cut.},
}

@inproceedings{taylorhelmick2000negative,
  title = {The Negative Consequences of Being a Good Boy Scout},
  author = {Taylor-Helmick, Tracy and Ivanoff, Jason},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The boy scout motto - "always be prepared" - may lead to rapid responses when a wilderness creature attacks suddenly. But when it comes to reacting to visual targets, responses may be slowed by prior (motor) preparation. We presented participants with two peripheral visual targets to which speeded spatially-compatible button-press responses were required. On a random half of the trials, a Stop Signal was presented at a variable delay following the First Target. Participants were instructed to withhold a response to the First Target when the Stop Signal appeared. Their ability to do so varied with the interval between the First Target and the Stop Signal appearance: The longer the delay, the less likely the participant was to withhold the prepared response. We examined how reaction times to the Second Target varied with the probability of canceling a response to the First Target. Although the results are preliminary, they suggest that preparing a response to the First Target slows the speed of making that same response to the Second Target. More importantly, the degree of slowing is related to the degree of prior motor preparation: The more prepared the First Target response is (i.e., the more difficult it is to cancel), the greater the inhibitory aftereffects may be.},
}

@inproceedings{boehnke2000what,
  title = {What 'coon you say about brain circuits using local inactivation?},
  author = {Boehnke, Susan and Rasmusson, Doug},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The raccoon has proved a great model for investigating cortical reorganization after peripheral denervations (e.g. amputation) due to their enlarged representations of the forepaw digits. In the raccoon cortex, a large sensory evoked potential (SEP) occurs in response to electrical stimulation of the corresponding digit - an "on-focus" response. Stimulation of a neighbouring digit evokes a smaller SEP - an "off-focus" response. It has been hypothesized that the off-focus response is conveyed through intracortical circuits from one digit representation to another and that these corticocortical pathways may contribute to the patterns of cortical reorganization observed in this species. We examined this hypothesis by recording on- and off-focus SEPs from 2 neighbouring digit cortical regions and examining the change in SEPs during a selective, reversible inactivation of one region using lidocaine and tetrodotoxin. Although the drugs blocked the "on-focus" response in the inactivated area, this did not result in a significant decrease in the amplitude of the "off-focus" response from the neighbouring cortical digit area. This indicates that changes in corticocortical connections may not play a major role in reorganization following amputation.},
}

@inproceedings{valdivia2000quality,
  title = {Quality of Life in Patients with Vagal Nerve Stimulators},
  author = {Valdivia, Ivan and Penner, Marsha and McGlone, Jeannette and Munk, Shirley and Clarke, David and Sadler, Mark},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {People with chronic epilepsy may experience a quality of life that is not optimal. Patients whose seizures are resistant to medication and who are not eligible for brain surgery may now be able to use Vagal Nerve Stimulation (VNS) as an alternative treatment. While the study of Quality of Life in persons with epilepsy is researched, information regarding the Quality of Life of patients using VNS is not. This study aims to examine Quality of Life in a VNS implantation group and two control groups: I-those who have undergone temporal lobe resectioning, and 2-those who are maintained on medications alone. Two separate measures of Quality of Life (i.e., the Quality of Life in Epilepsy-89, and the Quality of Life Questionnaire) are administered immediately before implantation of the VNS and again at a year follow-up. Preliminary data will be presented.},
}

@inproceedings{barresi2000evolution,
  title = {The evolution, history, and development of consciousness: A sketch},
  author = {Barresi, John},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {In the present talk I will give an overview of the evolution, history and development of consciousness. Obviously, it will only be a sketch. Basically, the issue is 'why consciousness'? What's consciousness for? How did it evolve to the level we find it in the human species? How did consciousness change historically in the human species? And, how does consciousness develop during the life of an individual human person? I promise to give answers to all of these questions. Whether you will believe my answers is quite another issue. But what can you expect from a ten-minute sketch?},
}

@inproceedings{braaksma2000neuropharmac,
  title = {Neuropharmacology and neurobiology of general anesthetics: the mystery of human consciousness},
  author = {Braaksma, Deanna},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Can the nature of consciousness be quantified, located, and understood within the human brain? Prevention of conscious awareness is a main goal of general anaesthesia. Examining (1) the molecular mechanisms of action of diverse anesthetic agents on various sites of the brain, (2) the similarities and differences between neuronal systems of anaesthetized and non-anaesthetized brains, and (3) the effects of anesthetics on higher brain functioning using functional brain imaging may be a fundamental empirical first step toward the eventual understanding human consciousness. The current presentation will outline what is known about the neurobiology and pharmacology of general anesthesia (e.g., NMDA receptors, Ach neurotransmitters, neuronal proteins, cortical-thalamic interactions, whole-brain metabolism), and will attempt to relate it to current models of consciousness (e.g., Rosenthal's metarepresentation, 1990; Tulving's multiple systems, 1998).},
}

@inproceedings{christie2000now,
  title = {"Now you see it, now you don't: Or did you?"},
  author = {Christie, John and Barresi, John},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Part of a recent experiment by John Christie and John Barresi will be presented as an example of the use of psychophysical methods in studying consciousness. The pitfalls, and controversies around these methods will be mentioned and hopefully incite much painful thought. Questions will be entertained but not necessarily answered.},
}

@inproceedings{johnson2000adult,
  title = {Adult egocentrism: Conceptualization and a new measure},
  author = {Johnson, Ed},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Egocentrism is the tendency to construe events and persons according to private knowledge, without appreciating the privileged character of such construal. Although pervasive in young children, it is proposed that habitual egocentrism in adults reflects deficient development and awareness of the self- system. Accordingly, it is hypothesized that dispositional egocentrism in adults should be associated with inadequate self-knowledge, low self-regard, and heightened self-preoccupation, along with a reduced capacity for understanding and empathizing with others. Two studies of college students are presented in support of this hypothesis. In Study 1, a self-report measure of the disposition to respond egocentrically, the Egocentric Response Scale (ERS) is introduced. Greater egocentrism on the ERS was associated with alexithymia, lower self-esteem, rumination about the self, public self-consciousness, and immature empathy. Study 2 showed that the ERS correlated positively with a measure of attitudinal egocentrism, and that on observer versions of both scales observers' ratings exhibited consensus about targets' egocentrism, and correlated positively with self-ratings of egocentrism. Both scales correlated negatively with measures of self-knowledge, mature empathy, and decoding others' emotions from nonverbal signals.},
}

@inproceedings{matheson2000hard,
  title = {The Hard Problem of Consciousness: Bridging the Explanatory Gap},
  author = {Matheson, Bill},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Many (perhaps most) psychologists and neuroscientists believe that an adequate, materialistic understanding of brain and behaviour will entail an understanding of the mind and consciousness. There will be no irreducible or incompatible residue left to explain once our empirical investigations, and their theoretical interpretation, are complete. Some (perhaps most) philosophers, however, are skeptical of this optimistic outlook. They believe that the mind, and particularly consciousness, have properties which cannot be brought within the scope of scientific explanation. There is an explanatory gap between a complete physical story, and one which includes such conscious phenomena as qualia and values. Although we can expect that the easy problems of perception, learning, discrimination, and so on, will be solved through scientific methods, the hard problem of consciousness will prove to be much more difficult, and perhaps impossible.},
}

@inproceedings{hunt2000eliminating,
  title = {Eliminating the costs of task set reconfiguration},
  author = {Hunt, Amelia and Klein, Raymond},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Given insufficient time to fully prepare for a switch in task, a deterioration in performance on the first trial of a new task would be expected. The interest of researchers has been captured by the residual switch costs that surprisingly remain despite sufficient time to prepare. We used a very simple task to investigate the costs to reaction time and accuracy associated with changing between two different instructional sets every eight trials. Subjects responded to left and right visual targets by making either spatially compatible or incompatible button press responses. Subjects were cued which of these responses to make by the color of a border appearing on the perimeter of the display. The large costs to reaction time found at a 200 ms border-target SOA were completely eliminated at longer intervals between the border and the stimulus, but costs to accuracy remained. An identical task using saccades towards or away from the target in the place of button presses resulted in the elimination of costs to both accuracy and reaction time. This finding does not support the prevailing hypothesis that a portion of the task set reconfiguration process must await the arrival of the imperative stimulus to be completed. The differences between the saccadic and manual task switching results are discussed with respect to the compatibility of these otherwise identical tasks.},
}

@inproceedings{ivanoff2000switch,
  title = {Switch costs without task switching?},
  author = {Ivanoff, Jason and Hunt, Amelia},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {A change in task initially results in detriments to perlormance. These "switch costs" have been commonly attributed to the re-configuration of task set by way of executive control processes. However, it is not known whether a switch in task, per se, is responsible for switch costs. In this investigation, task instruction did not change and accordingly no switch costs should be observed if they are only due to a re-configuration of task set. Responses were based entirely on the non-spatial identity of targets, and spatial location was completely irrelevant to the correct perlormance of the task. Series of spatially corresponding and non-corresponding stimulus-response ensembles alternated within an experiment and the task set remained stable over the duration of the experiment. Although there were no changes in task, we observed robust switch costs at two relatively long response-stimulus intervals. The results call into question the general idea that switch costs must be the result of a re-configuration of task set.},
}

@inproceedings{klein2000using,
  title = {Using rapid serial visual presentation (RSVP) to explore the temporal dynamics of reflexive attention shifts.},
  author = {Klein, Ray and Dick, Bruce},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {The immediate effect of a cue in the periphery (e.g., a luminance increment) is the facilitation of processing in the vicinity of the cue. Although it is generally agreed that this facilitative effect reflects the consequence of an exogenously generated shift of attention to the cued location, some investigators have claimed that the facilitation reflects a response bias rather than a genuine improvement. When the cue in uninformative and there is, therefore, no reason to keep attention at the cued location, the facilitation is followed by a long lasting inhibitory aftereffect at the cued location which has been called inhibition of return (IOR). There is considerable interest in determining whether IO R's primary effect is to delay perceptual processing, responding, or shifting of attention. The RSVP paradigm, originally developed in the 1970's and recently popularized in studies of the "attentional blink," is ideally suited to contribute to this debate because of its emphasis on identification accuracy (minimal demands are placed on the motor system) and its temporal precision. The temporal dynamics of the facilitation and inhibition that follow an uninformative peripheral cue, as obtained from the dual-RSVP-stream peripheral cuing paradigm that we have developed for this purpose, will be illustrated.},
}

@inproceedings{hancock2000made,
  title = {Made you look - obligatory processing of faces},
  author = {Hancock, Jeff and Klein, Ray},
  booktitle = {26th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2000},
  abstract = {Considerable converging evidence from a wide range of fields (neurophysiology, neuropsychology, cognitive and developmental psychology) suggests that faces represent a special class of visual patterns handled by a system separate from other visual processing systems. The present study attempts to extend research on face perception by examining whether faces presented in the visual field capture attention in a stimulus-driven fashion. Black and white high contrast face and non-face (inverted or scrambled faces) images were presented in a dual stream Rapid Serial Visual Presentation (RSVP) paradigm. The streams consisted of randomly selected letters with a single target digit placed pseudo- randomly in one of the streams. Overall, when the digit was presented around the same time as the face (or shortly thereafter) its identification was better when the face was adjacent to the stream with the digit than when the face was near the opposite stream. The opposite pattern emerged as the interval between the appearance of the face and the digit increased. This pattern corresponds roughly with the prototypical pattern of Inhibition of Return and suggests that faces may capture attention. However, significant laterality effects were observed suggesting that the role of attention in perceiving faces may be differential across visual hemifields. These laterality effects are discussed in terms of recent neuroimaging and neuropsychological data suggesting that the perception of faces is highly lateralized.},
}

@inproceedings{purdy2001changes,
  title = {Changes to the object recognition system in patients with dementia of the Alzheimer's type},
  author = {Purdy, Keni and McMullen, Paddy and Freedman, M.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Do patients with Dementia of the Alzheimer's Type (DAT) show category-specific deficits in object identification, and if so do they arise from semantic or visual damage? Basic (e.g., dog) and subordinate (e.g., collie) level identifications require a large amount of visual processing, whereas superordinate (e.g., animal) level identification requires additional semantic processing beyond the basic level. DAT patients, normal elderly controls and college-aged controls completed an object verification task, where they decided whether line-drawings of living and non-living objects matched names at superordinate, basic or subordinate levels. Superordinate and subordinate identifications were equally difficult for DAT patients. Subordinate identifications were most difficult for all controls. A category-specific deficit for living objects was found with DAT patients, but only at the Superordinate level. This finding supports the notion that some differences between living and non-living objects have a semantic basis. These findings also characterize the nature of the semantic memory deficit in DAT.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{houghton2001comparison,
  title = {A comparison of HS mice in the Barnes Maze and the Morris Water Maze},
  author = {Houghton, Darryl and Stanford, Lianne and BrOy_n, Richard E.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The Monis water maze, which is frequently used as a test of learning and memory in rodents has been criticized as being a stressful paradigm in mice (Van der Staay, 2000: Physiol. Behav. 68, 599-602 & Brooks et al. 2000: Soc. Neurosci Abst. 30, #841.3). This stress may confound learning and memory. The Barnes maze (BM), a visual spatial task in which mice learn to escape from the center of a brightly- lit platform into a dark cage through 1 of 16 holes on the periphery, may be a less stressful alternative to the MWM. If these two tasks are accessing similar cognitive processes, measures of learning and memory in the MWM should be highly correlated with those of the BM. To test this hypothesis, we ran 34 Heterozygous Stock (HS) mice (IBG, CO, USA) in both the MWM and the BM. Mice in the MWM showed decreased escape latencies (EL) across days and increased EL on the first day of reversal. Mice in the BM had decreased EL in acquisition, but no increase in EL on the first day of reversal. The number of errors committed in the BM decreased over days and did increase on the first day of reversal. Escape latency and errors within the BM correlated for all measures of learning (.45 < r < .92, p < .0001},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{kablar2001information,
  title = {Information provided by skeletal muscle and lower sensory/motor neurons influence neuronal fate in the developing mouse brain},
  author = {Kablar, Boris and Rudnicki, Michael A},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Fetuses that develop without Myf5 and MyoD genes entirely lack skeletal myogenesis and lose spinal motor and proprioceptive neurons. To test whether extrinsic cues provided by the lacking structures influence neuronal precursor cell differentiation in various brain areas involved in motor control we assessed wild-type and mutant brains for structural and molecular differences. Anatomical milestones of the mutant brain appeared unaffected. However, the expression pattern of various molecular markers for neural progenitors and pyramidal neurons in the mutant motor cortex was downregulated. Consistently, some areas of the mutant extrapyramidal tract were also affected. Surprisingly, we were unable to detect any change in proliferation or cell death in the mutant neuroepithelium. Taken together, it appears that patterning mechanisms intrinsic to the areas for motor control specify the basic organization of its subdivisions. However, extrinsic cues seem to change intrinsic properties of neural progenitors and influence the ratios of the cell types they produce.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{marchand2001linking,
  title = {Linking neuropsychological and neuropsychological assessments},
  author = {Marchand, Yannick and D'Arcy, Ryan and Connolly, John},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {There is considerable potential for the use of event-related brain potentials (ERPs) for neurocognitive evaluation in a clinical setting. The objective of the current study was to evaluate a group of left-sided stroke patients with varying degrees of receptive language impairment using both neuropsychological testing and ERP assessment. It was hypothesized that ERPs will assess accurately receptive language function and correlate with the neuropsychological data. Data were collected from ten left-sided stroke patients, who were undergoing rehabilitation at the time of testing. ERPs were recorded during the computerized Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test-Revised (PPVT-R), which has graded levels of vocabulary difficulty. In the computerized PPVT, a picture is presented followed by a digitized spoken word that is either congruent or incongruent with the picture. The results provide a comprehensive demonstration of the efficacy of ERP neurocognitive assessment in a stroke population.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{allen2001induction,
  title = {Induction of Hsp27 in the cerebellum after focal cerebellar injury},
  author = {Allen, G.V and Chase, T and Sisca, L and Reynolds, J},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Heat shock protein induction is thought to play a role in neuroprotection after traumatic brain injury (TBI) or ischemic insults. Induction of the 70 kDa heat shock protein has been described in Purkinje cells following various types of brain injury. However, information regarding expression of the small 27 kDa heat shock protein (Hsp27) after focal cerebellar injury is lacking. In this study, we used a weight drop model of brain injury in the anesthetized rat to identify tissue damage and Hsp27 induction. Male, Sprague Dawley rats were anesthetized with isoflurane and a craniotomy (5.0 mm) was made over the left paravermal cerebellar cortex using manual manipulation with an auger drill bit. The bone flap was removed (dura intact) and brain injury was produced by dropping a 20-g brass weight (severe TBI=15 cm height, 300g/cm, mild TVI=2.5 cm height, 50g/cm) down a plexiglas guide tube onto a plexiglas piston (3.5 mm diameter). Immediately after trauma, the bone flap was replaced and sealed with dental cement. Control animals were treated the same except that they did not received a weight drop injury. The animals were killed at different time intervals after injury and brain sections were processed for the immunohistochemical detection of Hsp27 or stained with thionin. Hsp27 is not constitutively expressed in the cerebellum. Following mild or severe weight drop injury, Hsp 27 induction was observed in Purkinje cells and astrocyte-like cells located in the molecular and granular cellular layers. Hsp27-positive astrocyte-like cells were prominent in widespread regions of the cerebellar fiber tracts predominately ipsilaterally. Following severe TBI only, Hsp27 labeled neurons and glial cells were observed in the deep cerebellar nuclei. Thionin staining showed prominent chromatolysis in the Purkinje cell layer directly under the TBI site and gliotic scarring in the deep fiber tracts ipsilateral to the injury. The data demonstrates that induction of Hsp27 occurs in both cerebellar neuronal and neuroglial cell populations after traumatic cerebellar injury. The role of HSsp27 induction in promoting cell survival or providing protection against subsequent injury needs to be determined.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{mcmullen2001local,
  title = {Local Attentional Deficits, Prosopagnosia and Category-Specific Agnosia for Living Objects},
  author = {McMullen, Paddy and Hunt, Amelia and Purdy, Kerri},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {M.B., a 41 year old prosopagnosic with category-specific agnosia for living objects, was tested 10 years after her original testing session for her ability to 1) detect configural and element-based changes in schematic faces and non-faces, 2) process at global and local attentional levels and 3) verify the identity of living and non-living objects at different levels of categorization. In the face task, normal controls were more sensitive to element changes in faces and non-faces than to configural changes. M.B. showed equivalent and low sensitivity to both element and configural changes in faces. MB was much more sensitive to changes in nonfaces, with a normal pattern of greater sensitivity to elemental changes. She was also impaired at local processing of Navon-type figures in a divided attention task. Finally, normal controls showed a living advantage and more efficient decisions to basic names than subordinate or superordinate names when superordinate, basic or subordinate names of living and nonliving objects were matched to pictures. M.B. showed very deficient processing of subordinate names in this task. Interestingly, her category-specific deficit was not manifest 10 years after her original deficit was found. M.B. has a visual impairment that manifests as a general face-processing problem that may be linked to abnormal local attentional allocation. Her category-specific problems were likely of a more semantic nature.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{davis2001long,
  title = {Long-Term Kindling in Mice as a Model for Interictal Emotionality},
  author = {Davis, A.C. and Dodd, C. and Young, N. and Marchant, E.G.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Patients with temporal lobe epilepsy (TLE) not only suffer from recurrent spontaneous seizures but also show disturbances in interictal (between seizures) emotionality, i.e. depression and anxiety. Long-term kindling is an animal model that is used to study these increases in emotionality. Most of the research to date on kindling-induced emotionality has been done with rats, and none has been done with mice. The advantage of using mice in this model is that the use of transgenics may allow for a greater understanding of the neural mechanisms underlying long-term kindling-induced emotionality. The purpose of this study was two-fold: to determine the effects of kindling on emotionality in mice, and to determine a technique that would allow for a maximum survival rate in mice for the duration of the long-term stimulations. Mice were given either 30, 75 or sham stimulations, and were tested on the open field and elevated plus maze. Significant differences between kindled and control mice were found in time in the periphery of the open field, line crosses in five minutes in the open field and open arm entries on the elevated plus maze. Also the survival rate of the mice for the duration of the experiment was 78%. The results from this experiment suggest that kindling in mice does produce changes in emotionality and that it is possible to deliver long-term stimulations to mice. These results suggest that future studies using transgenics in the long-term kindling model may be possible.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{doucette2001didn,
  title = {"If I Didn't Know Better, I'd Think You Were Lying to Me... ": Influence of Pre-judgment Biases on Credibility Judgments"},
  author = {Doucette, Naomi and Birt, Angela R. and Porter, Stephen},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {This study examined the effect of judgment bias on the accuracy in detecting deception. One hundred and two participants judged the veracity of 12 video taped statements (6 honest and 6 deceptive) and were asked to make ratings of credibility. Participants were randomly assigned to one of three conditions: no bias, honesty bias, or deceptive bias. In the deceptive bias condition, participants were instructed that it was quite possible that the speakers in the videos were attempting to be deceptive. By contrast, participants in the honesty condition were instructed that the speakers were likely to be telling the truth. Participants in the no bias condition were led to believe that the purpose of the study was to simply judge the quality of memory reports and no mention of deception or honesty was made. Overall accuracy in detecting deception was at chance level across the three conditions. However, the instructional manipulation did bias judgments and the degree of bias depended on the nature of the instructions. The participants in the no bias condition were significantly less accurate than those participants asked to focus on either honesty or deception. The frequencies with which deceptive and honest judgments were made also varied across the conditions. The implications of such pre-judgment biases in the context of legal and forensic settings are discussed.},
  note = {Poster},
}

@inproceedings{houghton2001comparisona,
  title = {A comparison of HS mice in the Barnes Maze and the Morris Water Maze},
  author = {Houghton, Darryl and Stanford, Leanne and Brown, Richard E},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The Monis water maze, which is frequently used as a test of learning and memory in rodents has been criticized as being a stressful paradigm in mice (Van der Staay, 2000: Physiol. Behav. 68, 599-602 & Brooks et al. 2000: Soc. Neurosci Abst. 30, #841.3). This stress may confound learning and memory. The Barnes maze (BM), a visual spatial task in which mice learn to escape from the center of a brightlylit platform into a dark cage through 1 of 16 holes on the periphery, may be a less stressful alternative to the MWM. If these two tasks are accessing similar cognitive processes, measures of learning and memory in the MWM should be highly correlated with those of the BM. To test this hypothesis, we ran 34 Heterozygous Stock (HS) mice (IBG, CO, USA) in both the MWM and the BM. Mice in the MWM showed decreased escape latencies (EL) across days and increased EL on the first day of reversal. Mice in the BM had decreased EL in acquisition, but no increase in EL on the first day of reversal. The number of errors committed in the BM decreased over days and did increase on the first day of reversal. Escape latency and errors within the BM correlated for all measures of learning (.45 < r < .92, p < .0001 to .0072). Separately, each of these tasks has measured learning and memory. In comparing the two tasks, correlations for the escape latencies of the BM and MWM were calculated and all measures of learning [all days combined (r .24, p < .1969), day - one acquisition (r .03, p < .8775), all acquisition (r .13, p < .4822), day-one reversal (r .13, p < .4686), & last day of reversal (r .13, p < .4568)) or memory (r .05) were not significant. There were also no significant correlations between the BM (errors) and the MWM (EL) for any measure of learning [all days combined (r = -.15, p < .4011), day-one acquisition (r .01, p <.9545), all acquisition (r .13, p < .4965), day-one reversal (r=-.18, p < .3004), & last day of reversal (r = .04, p < .8229)) or memory (r =.10 for errors). These data suggest the cognitive processing for these two tasks may be different, and when comparing data between these tasks caution should be exercised.},
}

@inproceedings{danielawaschbusch2001thinking,
  title = {Thinking About ADHD: Is a Psychoeducational Perspective Useful in Understanding Attention- Deficit / Hyperactivity Disorder?},
  author = {Daniel A. Waschbusch, Ann Marie Penny --=--- - The purpose of the proposed study is to investigate whether or not recent theories of intelligence are useful in understanding children with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. Participants will be children aged to, including children with and ADHD, without and with and without learning disorders. In order to assign each child a diagnosis, parents will complete a series of questionnaires assessing the child's behaviour and each child will complete the Wide Range Achievement Test, third edition. Each child will also complete the Woodcock-Johnson Tests of Cognitive Abilities, third edition, which provides scores based on the Carroll-Horn-Cattell theory of intelligence. These scores will be analyzed for patterns within diagnostic groups, as well as differences between groups},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  note = {QA: no-abstract},
}

@inproceedings{ac2001kindling,
  title = {Kindling-induced emotionality in both male and female rats Wintink, AJ, Young, N, Davis},
  author = {AC and Gregus and A and Kalynchuk and LE},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Men and women with temporal lobe epilepsy often experience interictal (i.e. between seizure) emotional disturbances. Long-term kindling (i.e. repeated focal stimulations) in rats serves as a model to understand the nature of seizures and of interictal emotionality (i.e. anxious behavior in novel situations) but has not yet been used to investigate potential differences in emotionality between male and female rats. There is substantial reason to expect sex differences in interictal emotionality including clinical data showing that more women are diagnosed with anxiety related disorders than are men and the expression of anxiety can be manifested differently between men and women. In the present study, both short- (30 stimulations) and long- (99 stimulations) term kindling was used to assess differences in emotionality in both male and female rats. Rats were assessed on behavioral measures of anxiety and depression and sex differences were observed on some of the measures. The results provide the first examination of kindling-induced emotionality between male and female rats .},
}

@inproceedings{schellinck2001long,
  title = {Long-term effects of acute and chronic pain in infancy in mice},
  author = {Schellinck, Heather M. and Darrah, Matthew and Stanford, Lianne},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Exposure to pain during development has long been hypothsized to disrupt behaviour in later life. (Hebb, 1949 Organization of Behaviour). We investigated the influence of early pain experience on anxiety and learning and memory in mice. Neonatal mice were exposed to an acute pain, i.e., a tail snip at postnatal day 8 or chronic pain, i.e., paw pricks on postnatal days 8-14. When tested in an elevated plus maze on day 30, both acute and chronic pain mice showed behavioural changes indicative of increased anxiety compared with control animals. The effects included a reduction in open arm entries, percent time spent in the open arms and a decrease in head dips. In addition, chronic pain animals showed a greater decrease in time spent in the open arms and in number of entries into the open arms as well as an increase in stretch attends compared with acute pain animals. There were no differences in the number of line crossings in the experimental and control animals. This pattern of results would suggest that the pain-exposed animals showed an overall increase in risk assessment, a behaviour associated with hypervigilance.in humans. In contrast, when tested in the Morris Water Maze, these mice demonstrated an intact working memory in a three-day acquisition task as well as in a probe trial and reversal trials. Thus, it appears that their increased anxiety did not adversely effect their performance in a spatial working memory task. Overall, these results reflect the potential role of early experience in influencing behaviour in adult animals.},
}

@inproceedings{lefebvre2001event,
  title = {An event-related brain potential (ERP) study of attention/working memory},
  author = {Lefebvre, Celeste and Connolly, John and Eskes, Gail},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The purpose of this study is to adapt two commonly used standardized neuropsychological measures of attention/working memory for computer presentation and simultaneous ERP recordings. This study will investigate the effectiveness of ERPs to determine working memory capabilities, as measured by the Digit Span and Spatial Span tasks from the Wechsler Memory Scale-III, in a normal population of undergraduate students. Each subject will be administered the traditional and computerized version of one of the two tasks. We hypothesize that 1) an individual's results on the computerized version of the Digit Span or Spatial Span tasks will be comparable to their results on the task when it is traditionally administered 2) the ERP components will reflect attention/memory processes and can determine when a person has reached the capacity of their attention span/working memory and 3) the differential ERP response pattern will be observable on an individual subject level.},
}

@inproceedings{mitchell2001initial,
  title = {Initial Recovery of Vision after Early Monocular Deprivation in Kittens is Faster When Both Eyes Are Open},
  author = {Mitchell, Donald E. and Gingras, Guy and Kind, Peter C.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The mild effects of binocular as compared to monocular visual deprivation led to the widely held view that the plasticity observed in the mammalian visual cortex during development reflects the operation of competitive interactions between the two eyes for synaptic space. More recent evidence suggests that inputs from the two eyes compete for limiting amounts of a retrograde molecule such as a neurotrophin, and active neurons can compete more efficiently than less active neurons. Competitive mechanisms, however, cannot explain the physiological and behavioural recovery in the deprived eye observed during a subsequent period of binocular vision in cats. Here we show, in direct comparisons of the speed of visual recovery in the deprived eye of kittens following a 6 day period of monocular deprivation, that recovery is initially faster in the situation where both eyes are open (binocular recovery) than with reverse lid-suture, where the animal is forced to employ the originally deprived eye. This state of affairs, which lasted for 4 - 8 days, is difficult to reconcile with accounts of synaptic plasticity based upon binocular competition but is consistent with homosynaptic mechanisms such as the model proposed by Bienstock, Cooper and Munro (the BCM Model).},
}

@inproceedings{ivanoff2001exogenous,
  title = {Exogenous orienting without awareness depends on attentional control settings},
  author = {Ivanoff, Jason},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Exogenous orienting, to a sudden-onset peripheral cue is thought to occur semi-automatically. Typically, exogenous orienting exhibits a biphasic pattern: responses to targets are initially facilitated by the cue but later they are inhibited (inhibition of return; IOR). Exogenous orienting to a cue is not fully automatic because it depends on the cue and target sharing a particular quality (e.g., sudden-onset). Thus, exogenous orienting is said to depend on the establishment of an attentional control setting. McCormick (1997) demonstrated that peripheral cues presented below a threshold of awareness attract attention and subsequently facilitate target processing. Interestingly, at late cue-target onset asynchronies he did not observe IOR, even though this is a robust effect often observed with exogenous cues. In the present study, masked and unmasked sudden-onset cues were presented under two conditions. In the first condition, the task was to respond rapidly to the onset of a target. Although the target task was the same in the second condition, the cue was detected and localized at the end of trial. IOR was present with and without masks in the first condition, but facilitation was not observed when the cues were masked. In the second condition, facilitation was observed for masked and unmasked cues, but IOR was not observed with masked cues. The results suggest that assessing cue awareness establishes a set for searching and this set gives rise to facilitation regardless of whether or not the cue can be consciously localized.},
}

@inproceedings{walsh2001attachment,
  title = {Attachment Security, Maternal Sensitivity, and Children's Response to Pain: An Internal Working Model of Pain},
  author = {Walsh, Trudi},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {This study will examine the predictive validity of attachment security and pain behaviour following both everyday pain incidents and acute pain incidents. The present study will be conducted with a cohort of fifty, five-year-old children, followed since 6 months of age, and their mothers. The children's faces will be videotaped during their 5-year medically indicated inoculation shot. Children's pain reaction will be coded using the Children's Facial Coding Scale and parent-child interactions will be assessed with the Child Adult Medical Procedure Interaction Scale. Following the needle, both mothers and children will provide ratings of subjective pain intensity and pain behaviour. Mothers will also complete diaries following four everyday pain incidents that their child experiences. Included in the diary is information concerning the child's reaction and subsequent parental response. Quality of attachment will be assessed using a Separation-Reunion procedure, the Separation Anxiety Test, and the Pain and Relationship Task. It is hypothesized that attachment security classification will predict children's response to and behaviour following painful incidents. The mediating effect of maternal sensitivity, initially collected at both 6 and 18 months of age, will be also examined. Multimodal procedures will also be used to examine the role of third variables that may account for these potential relations. These will include receptive language, emotional regulation, and emotional awareness. Tl 6.},
}

@inproceedings{genes2001will,
  title = {Will Brown and Chris Moore},
  author = {genes, Good and asymmetry, fluctuating and jealousy, human},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Ancestrally extrapair copulations (EPC) likely exerted adaptive pressures on hominids. One adaptive solution to reducing the probability of EPC is jealous emotions. Jealousy may be an adaptive strategy designed to retain one's mate. If jealousy was an ancestral mate retention tactic, then individuals more likely to be philandered upon should be more jealous. A predictor of likelihood to be philandered upon may be developmental instability. Developmental stability (DS) is a heritable indicator of an organism's ability to buffer environmental and genetic perturbances. DS is measured indirectly via fluctuating asymmetry (FA). FA is the deviation from perfect bilateral symmetry in normally bilateral traits. The less deviation from perfect symmetry is believed to be an intrinsically unfalsifiable indicator of 'good genes.' As predicted, more asymmetric individuals (as measured by digital calipers with .0lmm accuracy) were more jealous. FA accounted for substantial proportion of variance in self-reported jealousy. Findings are consistent with jealousy being a condition-dependent mate retention tactic in humans. Tl 7.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15 at: 'Good genes, fluctuating asymmetry and hu'},
}

@inproceedings{boehnke2001listening,
  title = {Listening for chaos amid order, or order amid chaos},
  author = {Boehnke, Susan and Hall, Susan and Marquardt, Torsten and Phillips, Dennis},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The listening brain generates auditory images with a location by examining the correlation between the sound waveforms that reach the two ears. If the sounds reaching the two ears are perfectly correlated (+ORDER) we perceive a compact sound image with a distinct location. If the two ears receive independent uncorrelated sounds (CHAOS), the perception is spatially diffuse and has no "location", like the noise of wind rustling leaves in a forest. We can digitally generate another, unnatural, type of perfectly correlated signal in which the signal phase at one ear is perfectly opposite to that of the signal reaching the other ear (-ORDER). This is perceptually somewhat compact, but doesn't have an easily specifiable "location". We have been examining the shortest detectable duration of each of these sounds when they occur between markers of another type: What is the shortest duration of ORDER you can detect in an ongoing stream of CHAOS, or of CHAOS in ORDER. It is much easier to detect the latter. Tl 8.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15 at: 'Listening for chaos amid order, or order'},
}

@inproceedings{elgar2001dieting,
  title = {Dieting and body dissatisfaction: An epidemiological survey of health behaviours in Canadian adolescents},
  author = {Elgar, Frank and Clancy, Christine and King, Alan J.C.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Identifying socio-demographic trends and psychological and behavioural correlates of dieting and body dissatisfaction (BD) in adolescents helps to identify those at greater risk of developing eating disorders. Analyses were performed on data collected from the Health Behaviours in School-Aged Children study in which 11,272 Canadian adolescents from grades 6 through 10 participated. Both BD and dieting were most prevalent among older and female adolescents, and BD increased the likelihood of dieting threefold. Other factors that increased the likelihood of dieting were depressed mood and low self- confidence. Adolescents who socialized more with peers, smoked more and consumed more alcohol were more likely to be dieting, suggesting peer influences on eating behaviours are pervasive during adolescence. Also, breakfast skipping was more closely related to BD and dieting than to family income, suggesting school lunch programs targeted to adolescents from low-income families should inform all adolescents about the risks associated with unnecessary dieting.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15 at: 'Dieting and body dissatisfaction: An epi'},
}

@inproceedings{hancock2001matt,
  title = {Matt Stone looks just ravishing in his pink dress" Irony in computer-mediated conversations.},
  author = {Hancock, Jeff and Dunham, Philip},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The text-based conversations that occur in email and internet chat environments eliminate many of the non-verbal signals, such as facial expressions and tone of voice, that we rely on to interpret a speaker's intent. The present study assessed the impact of computer-mediated communication (CMC) on the use of ironic forms (e.g., irony, hyperbole, understatement, rhetorical questions) in conversations between strangers. Given the reduction in the cues available in CMC to signal irony, we expected less use of irony in this impoverished environment than in face-to-face conversations. Comparison of 40 conversations across these two communicative environments indicated that, contrary to initial expectations, substantially more ironic language was produced in the CMC condition. This general finding has several implications for current theoretical accounts of the comprehension and production of verbal irony.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15-split3 at: 'Matt Stone looks just ravishing'},
}

@inproceedings{bernier2001neurobiology,
  title = {Neurobiology of sleep deprivation effects on mood in major depressive disorder},
  author = {Bernier, Denise},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {The goal of this pilot study is to assess the neurotransmitter changes in the brain that correlate with the improvement of mood in depression. Sleep deprivation therapy has consistently shown an acute, although transient, improvement of depressive symptoms in more than half of patients suffering from major depression. A test-retest magnetic resonance spectroscopy will be performed before and after half a night of sleep deprivation in a sample of female patients (n=12) in their twenties, suffering from major unipolar depression. We will investigate the medial prefrontal cortex, which was already identified by brain imaging studies as showing metabolic differences before and after sleep deprivation in responders, and the limbic structures, which have been shown to be involved in emotional expression. We expect the glutamatergic peak on the MRS spectra to change in association with changes in mood.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15-split3 at: 'Neurobiology of sleep deprivation'},
}

@inproceedings{forestell2001using,
  title = {Using Taste Reactivity to Measure Shifts in the Palatability of Conditioned Taste Cues},
  author = {Forestell, Catherine A. and LoLordo, Vincent M.},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {Tastes become more preferred after they have been paired with sugar reinforcement in a classical conditioning paradigm. The mechanism involved in the formation of conditioned taste preferences is not clear. It is possible that conditioned preferences occur because animals learn to expect calories upon consumption of the taste cue. Alternatively, the conditioning procedure may produce an increase in the palatability of the taste cue. Typically the taste reactivity test is used to assess the palatability of tastes. This test involves measuring a rat's hedonic and aversive affective responses to oral infusions of taste solutions. In this talk I will describe some of the taste reactivity experiments currently being conducted in our laboratory to assess palatability shifts in conditioned taste cues.},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15-split3-split2 at: 'T21. Using Taste Reactivity to Measure S'},
}

@inproceedings{schellinckl2001challenges,
  title = {Challenges of running research in a large laboratory class: An animal experiment where the researchers outnumber the animals by 30 to 1},
  author = {Schellinck(l), Heather and Hoffman(!), Ron and Services, John MacDonald(2). (1) Department of Psychology (2) Academic Computing},
  booktitle = {27th Annual In-House Convention, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University},
  year = {2001},
  abstract = {As part of the continuing evolution of the introductory psychology class (P 1001) into a laboratory class, this past year an animal research project was incorporated into the curriculum. Eighteen mice were assigned to either of two groups. Mice in the experimental group received caffeine in their drinking water. The mice were then observed in an open field apparatus, and experimenters recorded several behaviours. With over 600 potential experimenters, the logistics were challenging. In this talk, we describe how live observations were combined with additional observations recorded on digital video and presented over the internet. The preparations were not trivial, but the outcome was a success in several ways. T23. Construction and Initial Validation of a Daily Version of the Fatigue Impact Scale (D-FIS) John Fisk and Susan Doble Introduction: The Fatigue Impact Scale (FIS) has been developed as a symptom-specific profile measure of health-related quality of life (HRQoL). Its item content reflects subjects' attribution of problems to fatigue in the areas of physicaCcognftive, and psychosocial functioning. The FIS was initially developed for cross-sectional studies of medical conditions in which fatigue is a chronic symptom. Thus, it had not been designed to be a responsive measure of daily changes in fatigue. The present study describes the development and initial validation study of an adaptation of the FIS for use in conditions in which fatigue symptoms are of acute onset or have significant daily variation. Methods: Items for the Daily F_MigueImpact Scale (D-FIS) were selected from the pool of original FIS items with the aid of Rasclianalyses of existing data. The reduced, 18-item FIS was administered to a sample of 93 subjects with flu-like illness, some of whom were followed for a 21-day period. Rasch analyses were used to further reduce the scale to a minimum number of items that represented a unidimensional measure of self-reported fatigue impact. Results: The resulting 8-item D-FIS demonstrated good relations to ratings of other flu symptoms and to general ratings of HRQoL. It also proved to be a responsive measure, demonstrating significant reduction in fatigue impact for those subjects that were followed longitudinally. Moreover, subjective ratings of fatigue impact were associated with work hours lost and estimated work productivity for those subjects who did work for pay during},
  note = {QA: needs-split-review; Split from T15-split3-split2 at: 'T22. Challenges of running research in a'},
}

